     these are wall-clock and which (if any) are monotonic. -->

## The Y2K38 cliff

Any system that stores time as a 32-bit signed number of *seconds*
since 1970 will wrap on **19 January 2038 at 03:14:07 UTC**. On the
next second, the counter overflows and the year becomes 1901.

Motoi uses 64-bit-safe numbers (up to `2^53`, per Chapter 7), and
milliseconds — so Motoi is fine into the year 285,000-something. But
any external system you talk to might not be. Check the ceiling.

## Duration arithmetic — the algebra in code

Chapter opens with the four kinds of time. Here's the arithmetic laid
out with runnable examples. Assume the `instant` / `duration` shapes
from earlier.

**Adding durations.** Two durations add cleanly. `500 ms + 250 ms` is
`750 ms`. No timezone. No offset. Just numbers.

```
(+ 500 250)
;; -> 750
```

**Subtracting instants.** Two instants subtract to a duration —
*how long between them*. The result is a duration, not another
instant.

```
(- 2000 1000)
;; -> 1000
```

That's a millisecond duration of 1 second. If you tag the result
you'd write `(duration 1000)`.

**Scaling a duration.** Multiply a duration by a scalar and you get a
duration. Ten intervals of 500 ms is 5 seconds.

```
(* 500 10)
;; -> 5000
```

**Dividing durations.** Divide a duration by a duration and you get a
*ratio* — a unitless number. *How many of B fit in A?*

```
(/ 5000 500)
;; -> 10
```

Ten 500-ms intervals fit in 5 seconds. That is a dimensionless number
you can use to schedule *n* ticks across a span.

**Dividing a duration by a scalar.** Duration divided by a plain
scalar gives a duration.

```
(/ 5000 10)
;; -> 500
```

Five seconds split into ten pieces is 500 ms per piece.

DO: treat `duration ÷ duration` as a *count* — a number that means
'how many of these fit in that'.
DON'T: assume `duration - duration` gives you a duration and
`duration + duration` gives you an instant. That's not the algebra.
WHY: same units on both sides means you're subtracting/adding same-
kind values. Different units means one side is a ratio, the other a
delta. The type shape refuses the confusion.

## Wall clock vs monotonic — a picture

Wall clock: the number your watch reads. Can go backward (NTP,
daylight saving, user changes clock, leap seconds under some rules).

Monotonic: an ever-increasing count of ticks since some arbitrary
start point (usually system boot). Cannot go backward. Meaningless
across boots or across machines.

If you measure *how long a request took*:

```
;; Pseudocode showing the shape, not verbatim frozen verbs.
(define start (time/now))          ;; wall time — could jump
(do-the-thing)
(define end (time/now))
(- end start)                       ;; could be negative if wall jumped
```

If your wall clock jumped backward during the request (because NTP
noticed a 3-second drift), the subtraction returns a negative
number and your dashboard shows *request took -2.7 seconds*.
Monotonic time avoids this. Use it for durations. Reserve wall
clock for *what time was it* questions where the answer needs to
match what a human sees on a clock.

## ISO 8601 as the wire format

When you write a time value to disk, or over the network, or into a
log line, use ISO 8601 with the `Z` suffix. Every language on earth
can parse it. Every human on earth can read it.

```
(time/iso)
;; -> \"2026-07-17T03:23:42.945Z\"
```

The parts:

- `2026-07-17` — year, month, day
- `T` — separator between date and time
- `03:23:42.945` — hour, minute, second, milliseconds
- `Z` — Zulu / UTC

Never write a bare `2026-07-17 03:23:42`. Somebody will parse it as
local time in their timezone and everything downstream will drift.
The `Z` is the whole point.

## Recap

- Time is not one value. It is *at least* four: wall time, UTC
  instant, duration, monotonic.
- `time/now` returns a UTC instant in milliseconds. `time/iso`
  formats it as an ISO 8601 string.
- Adding two instants is meaningless. Subtracting two instants gives
  a duration. Adding a duration to an instant gives an instant.
- Store times as UTC instants. Display in the user's timezone.
- Daylight saving invalidates the assumption that wall time advances
  monotonically. Schedule against UTC.
- Wall time can jump backward. Measure elapsed time with monotonic
  clocks where available.
- 32-bit epoch-second systems fail on 19 January 2038. Know what
  width the systems you talk to use.

Next: how to compare values correctly — currencies, floats, times,
and everything else that isn't just `=`.")

(example :ref "ch8-now-ms"
         :code "(number? (time/now))"
         :expected #t
         :teaching "time/now returns a number. The value itself changes every call.")
(example :ref "ch8-iso-string"
         :code "(string? (time/iso))"
         :expected #t)
(example :ref "ch8-plain-add-nonsense"
         :code "(+ 1784258622855 1784258622855)"
         :expected 3568517245710
         :teaching "Motoi lets you add two moments. The result is meaningless.")
(example :ref "ch8-shape-add-ok"
         :code "(begin (define (instant ms) (list 'instant ms)) (define (duration ms) (list 'duration ms)) (define (instant-ms i) (cadr i)) (define (duration-ms d) (cadr d)) (define (time+ a b) (cond ((and (eq? (car a) 'instant) (eq? (car b) 'duration)) (instant (+ (instant-ms a) (duration-ms b)))) (else (list 'error 'time+ 'bad-shapes (car a) (car b))))) (time+ (instant 1000) (duration 500)))"
         :expected "(instant 1500)")
(example :ref "ch8-shape-add-refuse"
         :code "(begin (define (instant ms) (list 'instant ms)) (define (duration ms) (list 'duration ms)) (define (time+ a b) (cond ((and (eq? (car a) 'instant) (eq? (car b) 'duration)) (list 'instant (+ (cadr a) (cadr b)))) ((and (eq? (car a) 'instant) (eq? (car b) 'instant)) (list 'error 'time+ 'cannot-add-two-instants)) (else (list 'error 'time+ 'bad-shapes)))) (time+ (instant 1000) (instant 500)))"
         :expected "(error time+ cannot-add-two-instants)")
(example :ref "ch8-dur-plus-dur"
         :code "(+ 500 250)"
         :expected 750)
(example :ref "ch8-inst-minus-inst"
         :code "(- 2000 1000)"
         :expected 1000)
(example :ref "ch8-dur-scale"
         :code "(* 500 10)"
         :expected 5000)
(example :ref "ch8-dur-ratio"
         :code "(/ 5000 500)"
         :expected 10)
(example :ref "ch8-dur-split"
         :code "(/ 5000 10)"
         :expected 500)
